Examining Transit-Oriented Development in Boston between 2009 and 2019

With transportation as a fundamental demand of people to access services and other urban resources, Transit-Oriented Development has contributed to enhancing the ease of access by creating dense and mixed communities close to the transit stations. However, households and individuals from various socio-economic backgrounds may value public transit differently. To find out the Transit-Oriented Development conditions in Boston, the brief will discuss how areas of Transit-Oriented Development in Boston are correlated with several socio-economic indicators between 2009 and 2019.

1. Wrangling the ACS data for 2009 and 2019.

# Load Libraries

library(tidyverse)
library(tidycensus)
library(sf)
library(kableExtra)
library(gridExtra)

options(scipen=999)
options(tigris_class = "sf")

source("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/urbanSpatial/Public-Policy-Analytics-Landing/master/functions.r")

palette5 <- c("#f0f9e8","#bae4bc","#7bccc4","#43a2ca","#0868ac")
census_api_key("c225553bc2ab27557539c33de3ebe928e378d800", overwrite = TRUE)
#Get census tract data
tracts19 <-  
  get_acs(geography = "tract",
          variables = c("B25026_001E","B02001_002E",
                        "B15001_050E","B15001_009E",
                        "B19013_001E", "B25058_001E",
                        "B06012_002E", "B01002_001E"), 
          year=2019, state=25,
          county=025, geometry=TRUE) %>% 
  st_transform('ESRI:102686')

tracts09 <-  
  get_acs(geography = "tract",
          variables = c("B25026_001E","B02001_002E",
                        "B15001_050E","B15001_009E",
                        "B19013_001E", "B25058_001E",
                        "B06012_002E", "B01002_001E"), 
          year=2009, state=25,
          county=025, geometry=TRUE) %>% 
  st_transform('ESRI:102686')
# Let's "spread" the data into wide form

tracts19 <- 
  tracts19 %>%
  dplyr::select( -NAME, -moe) %>%
  spread(key = variable, value = estimate) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B25026_001, 
         Whites = B02001_002,
         FemaleBachelors = B15001_050, 
         MaleBachelors = B15001_009,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001, 
         MedRent = B25058_001,
         TotalPoverty = B06012_002,
         MedAge = B01002_001)

tracts09 <- 
  tracts09 %>%
  dplyr::select( -NAME, -moe) %>%
  spread(key = variable, value = estimate) %>%
  rename(TotalPop = B25026_001, 
         Whites = B02001_002,
         FemaleBachelors = B15001_050, 
         MaleBachelors = B15001_009,
         MedHHInc = B19013_001, 
         MedRent = B25058_001,
         TotalPoverty = B06012_002,
         MedAge = B01002_001)

# Let's create new rate variables using mutate

tracts19 <- 
  tracts19 %>%
  mutate(pctWhite = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Whites / TotalPop, 0),
         pctBachelors = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, ((FemaleBachelors + MaleBachelors) / TotalPop), 0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),
         year = "2019") %>%
  dplyr::select(-Whites,-FemaleBachelors,-MaleBachelors,-TotalPoverty)

tracts09 <- 
  tracts09 %>%
  mutate(pctWhite = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, Whites / TotalPop, 0),
         pctBachelors = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, ((FemaleBachelors + MaleBachelors) / TotalPop), 0),
         pctPoverty = ifelse(TotalPop > 0, TotalPoverty / TotalPop, 0),
         year = "2009") %>%
  dplyr::select(-Whites,-FemaleBachelors,-MaleBachelors,-TotalPoverty)

# Combine the tracts from the two years
allTracts <- rbind(tracts09,tracts19)

2. Wrangling the MBTA Rapid Transit Stop data.

mbta <- st_read("https://hub.arcgis.com/datasets/massgis::mbta-rapid-transit-stops.geojson", quiet = TRUE)

# Remove Silver Line Stops
mbta <- mbta %>% filter(LINE != "SILVER")

mbta <- mbta %>% st_transform(st_crs(tracts19))
#create .5 mile buffer from stations
stopBuffer <- st_buffer(mbta, 2640)

stopUnion <- st_union(stopBuffer)

mbtaBuffers <- 
  rbind(
     stopBuffer %>%
      mutate(Legend = "Buffer") %>%
      dplyr::select(Legend),
     stopUnion %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(Legend = "Unioned Buffer"))
buffer <- filter(mbtaBuffers, Legend=="Unioned Buffer")
selectCentroids <-
  st_centroid(tracts19)[buffer,] %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(., dplyr::select(tracts19, GEOID), by = "GEOID") %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  dplyr::select(TotalPop) %>%
  mutate(Selection_Type = "Select by Centroids")
#join TOD and non-TOD tracts by centroid method
allTracts.group <- 
  rbind(
    st_centroid(allTracts)[buffer,] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allTracts) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "TOD"),
    st_centroid(allTracts)[buffer, op = st_disjoint] %>%
      st_drop_geometry() %>%
      left_join(allTracts) %>%
      st_sf() %>%
      mutate(TOD = "Non-TOD")) %>%
  #adjust for inflation
  mutate(MedRent.inf = ifelse(year == "2009", MedRent * 1.19, MedRent),
         MedHHInc.inf = ifelse(year == "2009", MedHHInc * 1.19, MedHHInc)) 
#plot TOD vs non-TOD areas

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data=allTracts.group, mapping = aes(fill = TOD)) +
  geom_sf(data=mbta, aes(color = ""), size= 1.5, alpha = 0.7) +
   scale_color_manual(values = "black",
                     name = "MBTA Transit Stop") +
  labs(title="TOD and non-TOD Tracts", 
       subtitle="Suffolk County, MA", 
       caption="Figure 2.1") +
  mapTheme()

Figure 2.1 shows the geographical areas of TOD and Non-TOD tracts in Boston, with two linear clusters of TOD tracts crossing the city center.

Figure 3.1

Figure 3.1 illustrates the relationship between TOD and Non-TOD tracts in terms of median household income, median rent, percentage with Bachelors degree and median age in 2009 and 2019. Median household income and median rent have witnessed overall increase, particularly in the city center and surroundings. Meanwhile, there are generally higher percentage of people with bachelors degree in the TOD areas, and relatively people living in non-TOD areas have higher median age.

4. Dynamic changes of population and rent

# Calculate centroids
tract_centroids_all <- st_centroid(allTracts.group)
# Create half-mile buffers
tract_buffers_all <- st_buffer(tract_centroids_all, dist = 2640)

clipAll <-
  st_intersection(tract_buffers_all, mbta)

summaryTableAll <- clipAll %>%
  group_by(year, STATION) %>%
  summarize(Total_pop = sum(TotalPop, na.rm = TRUE),
           Rent = mean(MedRent.inf, na.rm = TRUE))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = st_union(tracts19), fill = "lightgray") +
  geom_sf(data = summaryTableAll, aes(size = Total_pop, fill = Total_pop), shape = 21,
          alpha = 0.7, show.legend = "point") +
  facet_wrap(~year) +
  scale_size_continuous(range = c(0.5, 12)) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = '#f0f9e8', high = '#0868ac') + 
  labs(title = "Population withn  1/2 Mile of Rapid Transit Stops", 
       subtitle = "Suffolk County", caption = "Figure 3.5") +
  mapTheme() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=20)) +
  guides(size = guide_legend(title = "Total Population", 
                             override.aes = list(alpha = 1, shape = 21)),
         fill = guide_legend(title = "Total Population"))

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = st_union(tracts19), fill = "lightgray") +
  geom_sf(data = summaryTableAll, aes(size = Rent, fill = Rent), shape = 21,

  facet_wrap(~year) +

         fill = guide_legend(title = "Total Population"))

The population within 1/2 miles of the stations generally remain similar in 2009 and 2019, while the rent has increased dramatically, particularly in the city center.

5. Change of mean rent in terms of the distance to stations

mbta_MRB <- multipleRingBuffer(st_union(mbta),
                                maxDistance = 31680,
                                interval =  2640)
tracts19.rings <- tracts19 %>% 
  select(GEOID, year) %>% 
  st_centroid() %>% 
  st_join(mbta_MRB, join = st_intersects) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(tracts19, GEOID, MedRent, year), 
            by=c("GEOID"="GEOID", "year"="year")) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(distance = distance / 5280) #convert to miles

tracts09.rings <- tracts09 %>% 
  select(GEOID, year) %>% 
  st_centroid() %>% 
  st_join(mbta_MRB, join = st_intersects) %>%
  st_drop_geometry() %>%
  left_join(dplyr::select(tracts09, GEOID, MedRent, year), 
            by=c("GEOID"="GEOID", "year"="year")) %>%
  st_sf() %>%
  mutate(distance = distance / 5280) #convert to miles

allTracts.rings <- rbind(tracts09.rings, tracts19.rings)

allTracts.rings.summary <- st_drop_geometry(allTracts.rings) %>%
    group_by(distance, year) %>%
    summarize(Mean_Rent = mean(MedRent, na.rm=T))

ggplot(allTracts.rings.summary,
       aes(distance, Mean_Rent, colour=year)) +
      geom_point(size=3) + 
  geom_line(size=2) +
  labs(title = "Rent as a Function of Distance from Transit Stop", subtitle = "Suffolk County",
       caption = "Figure 3.6") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=20))

Within 1 mile of the transit stops, the rent reached its highest when the property is closest to the stop and dropped in a sizeable extent. Between 2 to 3.5 miles, the mean rent generally remain stable and generally lower or at the same level compared with properties closer to the transit stops.

6. Conclusion

The findings of the socio-economic comparison between TOD and Non-TOD areas have illustrated that the neighborhoods within 1/2 miles of transit stops generally have higher concentration of younger population, higher rent, more people with bachelors degree and slightly higher median income. However, one limitation of the findings can result from the spatial bias that the souce of data is from census tracts, which is not detailed enough to fully represent the specific areas close to the transit stops. This can inform the TOD development to enhance the spatial equity to create more accessible public transit for wider range of people.
